#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:235 ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:245
msgid "Use after scope"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:237
msgid ""
"This check warns when a pointer or reference is used after the stack "
"variable it refers to has gone out of scope."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:246 ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:283
#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:322 ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:376
msgid "Correct"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:271 ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:282
msgid "Return of stack address"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:273
msgid ""
"This check warns when a function returns a pointer or reference to a stack-"
"allocated variable, which will be destroyed when the function returns, "
"leaving the caller with a dangling pointer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:310 ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:321
msgid "Dangling field"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:312
msgid ""
"This check warns when a constructor or method assigns a pointer to a stack-"
"allocated variable or temporary to a field of the class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:357 ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:375
msgid "Use after invalidation (experimental)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:359
msgid ""
"This check warns when a reference to a container element (such as an "
"iterator, pointer or reference) is used after a container operation that may "
"have invalidated it. For example, adding elements to ``std::vector`` may "
"cause reallocation, invalidating all existing iterators, pointers and "
"references to its elements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:366
msgid ""
"Container invalidation checking is highly experimental and may produce false "
"positives."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:400
msgid "Annotation Inference and Suggestions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:402
msgid ""
"In addition to detecting lifetime violations, the analysis can suggest "
"adding ``[[clang::lifetimebound]]`` to function parameters or methods when "
"it detects that a pointer/reference to a parameter or ``this`` escapes via "
"the return value. This helps improve API contracts and allows the analysis "
"to perform more accurate checks in calling code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:408
msgid ""
"To enable annotation suggestions, use ``-Wlifetime-safety-suggestions``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:422
msgid "Translation-Unit-Wide Analysis and Inference"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:424
msgid ""
"By default, lifetime analysis is intra-procedural for error checking. "
"However, for annotation inference to be effective, lifetime information "
"needs to propagate across function calls. You can enable experimental "
"translation-unit-wide analysis using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:429
msgid ""
"``-flifetime-safety-inference``: Enables inference of ``lifetimebound`` "
"attributes across functions in a TU."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:431
msgid ""
"``-fexperimental-lifetime-safety-tu-analysis``: Enables TU-wide analysis for "
"better inference results."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:437
msgid "Warning flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:439
msgid ""
"Lifetime safety warnings are organized into hierarchical groups, allowing "
"users to enable categories of checks incrementally. For example, ``-"
"Wlifetime-safety`` enables all dangling pointer checks, while ``-Wlifetime-"
"safety-permissive`` enables only the high-confidence subset of these checks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:445
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-all``: Enables all lifetime safety warnings, including"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:445
msgid ""
"dangling pointer checks, annotation suggestions, and annotation validations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:447
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety``: Enables dangling pointer checks from both the "
"``permissive`` and ``strict`` groups listed below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:449
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-permissive``: Enables high-confidence checks for "
"dangling pointers. **Recommended for initial adoption.**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:451
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-use-after-scope``: Warns when a pointer to a stack "
"variable is used after the variable's lifetime has ended."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:452
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-return-stack-addr``: Warns when a function returns a "
"pointer or reference to one of its local stack variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:453
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-dangling-field``: Warns when a class field is assigned a "
"pointer to a temporary or stack variable whose lifetime is shorter than the "
"class instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:455
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-strict``: Enables stricter and experimental checks. "
"These may produce false positives in code that uses move semantics heavily, "
"as the analysis might conservatively assume a use-after-free even if "
"ownership was transferred."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:457
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-use-after-scope-moved``: Same as ``-Wlifetime-safety-use-"
"after-scope`` but for cases where the variable may have been moved from "
"before its destruction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:458
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-return-stack-addr-moved``: Same as ``-Wlifetime-safety-"
"return-stack-addr`` but for cases where the variable may have been moved "
"from."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:459
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-dangling-field-moved``: Same as ``-Wlifetime-safety-"
"dangling-field`` but for cases where the variable may have been moved from."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:460
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-invalidation``: Warns when a container iterator or "
"reference to an element is used after an operation that may invalidate it "
"(Experimental)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:462
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-suggestions``: Enables suggestions to add ``[[clang::"
"lifetimebound]]`` to function parameters and ``this`` parameters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:464
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-intra-tu-suggestions``: Suggestions for functions local "
"to the translation unit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:465
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-cross-tu-suggestions``: Suggestions for functions "
"visible across translation units (e.g., in headers)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:467
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-validations``: Enables checks that validate existing "
"lifetime annotations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:469
msgid ""
"``-Wlifetime-safety-noescape``: Warns when a parameter marked with "
"``[[clang::noescape]]`` escapes the function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:472
msgid "Limitations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:475
msgid "Move Semantics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:476
msgid ""
"The analysis does not currently track ownership transfers through move "
"operations. Instead, it uses scope-based lifetime tracking: when an owner "
"goes out of scope, the analysis assumes the resource is destroyed, even if "
"ownership was transferred via ``std::move()`` or ``std::unique_ptr::"
"release()``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:481
msgid ""
"This means that if a pointer or view is created from an owner, and that "
"owner is later moved-from and goes out of scope, the analysis will issue a "
"``-Wlifetime-safety-*-moved`` warning. This warning indicates that the "
"pointer may be dangling, even though the resource may still be alive under a "
"new owner. These are often false positives when ownership has been safely "
"transferred."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:487
msgid ""
"To avoid these warnings and ensure correctness, follow the **\"move-first-"
"then-alias\"** pattern: create views or raw pointers *after* the ownership "
"transfer, sourcing them from the new owner rather than the original owner "
"that will go out of scope."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:492
msgid "For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:500
msgid "Anti-Pattern: Aliasing Before Move"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:501
msgid "Good Practice: Move-First-Then-Alias"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:537
msgid ""
"The same principle applies when moving ownership using ``std::unique_ptr::"
"release()``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:560
msgid "``std::unique_ptr`` with custom deleters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:561
msgid ""
"The analysis assumes standard ownership semantics for owner types like "
"``std::unique_ptr``: when a ``unique_ptr`` goes out of scope, it is assumed "
"that the owned object is destroyed and its memory is deallocated. However, "
"``std::unique_ptr`` can be used with a custom deleter that modifies this "
"behavior. For example, a custom deleter might keep the memory alive by "
"transferring it to a memory pool, or simply do nothing, allowing another "
"system to manage the lifetime."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:569
msgid ""
"Because the analysis relies on scope-based lifetime for owners, it does not "
"support custom deleters that extend the lifetime of the owned object beyond "
"the lifetime of the ``std::unique_ptr``. In such cases, the analysis will "
"assume the object is destroyed when the ``std::unique_ptr`` goes out of "
"scope, leading to false positive warnings if pointers to the object are used "
"afterward."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:599
msgid "Dangling Fields"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:600
msgid ""
"The lifetime analysis is intra-procedural. It analyzes one function or "
"method at a time. This means if a field is assigned a pointer to a local "
"variable or temporary inside a constructor or method, and that local's "
"lifetime ends before the method returns, the analysis will issue a ``-"
"Wlifetime-safety-dangling-field`` warning. It must do so even if no *other* "
"method of the class ever accesses this field, because it cannot see how "
"other methods are implemented or used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:619
msgid ""
"In this case, ``name_`` dangles after the constructor finishes. Even if "
"``data()`` is never called, the analysis flags the dangling assignment in "
"the constructor because it represents a latent bug. The recommended approach "
"is to ensure fields only point to objects that outlive the field itself, for "
"example by storing an owned object (e.g., ``std::string``) or ensuring the "
"borrowed object (e.g., one passed by ``const&``) has a sufficient lifetime."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:629
msgid "Performance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../LifetimeSafety.rst:631
msgid ""
"Lifetime analysis relies on Clang's CFG (Control Flow Graph). For functions "
"with very large or complex CFGs, analysis time can sometimes be significant. "
"To mitigate this, the analysis allows to skip functions where the number of "
"CFG blocks exceeds a certain threshold, controlled by the ``-flifetime-"
"safety-max-cfg-blocks=N`` language option."
msgstr ""
